# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tcl-lang
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] In computing, an **interpreter** is software that executes source code without first compiling it to machine code.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] An interpreted runtime environment differs from one that processes CPU-native executable code which requires translating source code before executing it.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] An interpreter may translate the source code to an intermediate format, such as bytecode.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] A hybrid environment may translate the bytecode to machine code via just-in-time compilation, as in the case of .NET and Java, instead of interpreting the bytecode directly.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] Before the widespread adoption of interpreters, the execution of computer programs often relied on compilers, which translate and compile source code into machine code.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] Early runtime environments for Lisp and BASIC could parse source code directly.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] Thereafter, runtime environments were developed for languages (such as Perl, Raku, Python, MATLAB, and Ruby), which translated source code into an intermediate format before executing to enhance runtime performance.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] Code that runs in an interpreter can be run on any platform that has a compatible interpreter.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] The same code can be distributed to any such platform, instead of an executable having to be built for each platform.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] Although each programming language is usually associated with a particular runtime environment, a language can be used in different environments.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] Interpreters have been constructed for languages traditionally associated with compilation, such as ALGOL, Fortran, COBOL, C and C++.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] In the early days of computing, compilers were more commonly found and used than interpreters because hardware at that time could not support both the interpreter and interpreted code and the typical batch environment of the time limited the advantages of interpretation.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] Interpreters were used as early as 1952 to ease programming within the limitations of computers at the time (e.g. a shortage of program storage space, or no native support for floating point numbers).
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] Interpreters were also used to translate between low-level machine languages, allowing code to be written for machines that were still under construction and tested on computers that already existed.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] The first interpreted high-level language was Lisp.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] Lisp was first implemented by Steve Russell on an IBM 704 computer.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] Russell had read John McCarthy's paper, "Recursive Functions of Symbolic Expressions and Their Computation by Machine, Part I", and realized (to McCarthy's surprise) that the Lisp *eval* function could be implemented in machine code.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] The result was a working Lisp interpreter which could be used to run Lisp programs, or more properly, "evaluate Lisp expressions".
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] The development of editing interpreters was influenced by the need for interactive computing.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] In the 1960s, the introduction of time-sharing systems allowed multiple users to access a computer simultaneously, and editing interpreters became essential for managing and modifying code in real-time.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] The first editing interpreters were likely developed for mainframe computers, where they were used to create and modify programs on the fly.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] One of the earliest examples of an editing interpreter is the EDT (Editor and Debugger for the TECO) system, which was developed in the late 1960s for the PDP-1 computer.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] EDT allowed users to edit and debug programs using a combination of commands and macros, paving the way for modern text editors and interactive development environments.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] to execute machine code for a hardware architecture different from the one running the interpreter.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] another computer system in order to run code written for that system.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] can be implemented in an interpreted language.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] Interpretive overhead is the runtime cost of executing code via an interpreter instead of as native (compiled) code.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] Interpreting is slower because the interpreter executes multiple machine-code instructions for the equivalent functionality in the native code.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] In particular, access to variables is slower in an interpreter because the mapping of identifiers to storage locations must be done repeatedly at run-time rather than at compile time.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] But faster development (due to factors such as shorter edit-build-run cycle) can outweigh the value of faster execution speed—especially when prototyping and testing when the edit-build-run cycle is frequent.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] An interpreter may generate an intermediate representation (IR) of the program from source code in order to achieve goals such as fast runtime performance.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] A compiler may also generate an IR, but the compiler generates machine code for later execution whereas the interpreter prepares to execute the program.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] These differing goals lead to differing IR design.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] Many BASIC interpreters replace keywords with single byte tokens which can be used to find the instruction in a jump table.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] Many BASIC interpreters can store and read back their own tokenized internal representation.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] There are various compromises between the development speed when using an interpreter and the execution speed when using a compiler.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] Some systems (such as some Lisps) allow interpreted and compiled code to call each other and to share variables.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] This means that once a routine has been tested and debugged under the interpreter it can be compiled and thus benefit from faster execution while other routines are being developed.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] Since the early stages of interpreting and compiling are similar, an interpreter might use the same lexical analyzer and parser as a compiler and then interpret the resulting abstract syntax tree.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] An expression interpreter written in C++.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] Just-in-time (JIT) compilation is the process of converting an intermediate format (i.e. bytecode) to native code at runtime.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] As this results in native code execution, it is a method of avoiding the runtime cost of using an interpreter while maintaining some of the benefits that led to the development of interpreters.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] Logic is specified as data formatted as a table.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] which is an intermediate format of logic compiled from a high-level language.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] is compiled to bytecode which is interpreted by an interpreter.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] One might say that this compiled code is machine code for a virtual machine – implemented by the interpreter.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] interpreter is similar to bytecode interpreter but instead of bytes, uses pointers.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] Each instruction is a word that points to a function or an instruction sequence, possibly followed by a parameter.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] The threaded code interpreter either loops fetching instructions and calling the functions they point to, or fetches the first instruction and jumps to it, and every instruction sequence ends with a fetch and jump to the next instruction.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] (AST), then interprets it directly, or uses it to generate native code via JIT compilation.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] In this approach, each sentence needs to be parsed just once.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] As an advantage over bytecode, AST keeps the global program structure and relations between statements (which is lost in a bytecode representation), and when compressed provides a more compact representation.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] Thus, using AST has been proposed as a better intermediate format than bytecode.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] However, for interpreters, AST results in more overhead than a bytecode interpreter, because of nodes related to syntax performing no useful work, of a less sequential representation (requiring traversal of more pointers) and of overhead visiting the tree.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] When the particular code segment is executed the interpreter simply loads or jumps to the opcode mapping in the template and directly runs it on the hardware.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] provides an abstraction layer as a hardware interpreter that implements machine code in a lower-level machine code.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] so that the high-level instructions can be designed and altered more freely.
[src:tcl-lang/interpreter-computing] It also facilitates providing complex multi-step instructions, while reducing the complexity of computer circuits.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] In computing, a **script** is a relatively short and simple set of instructions that typically automate an otherwise manual process.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] The act of writing a script is called **scripting**.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] A **scripting language** or **script language** is a programming language that is used for scripting.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Originally, scripting was limited to automating shells in operating systems, and languages were relatively simple.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Today, scripting is more pervasive and some scripting languages include modern features that allow them to be used to develop application software also.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] A scripting language can be a general-purpose programming language or a domain-specific language for a given environment.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] When embedded in an application, it may be called an *extension language*.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] A scripting language is sometimes referred to as very high-level programming language if it operates at a high level of abstraction, or as a *control language*, especially for job control languages on mainframe computers.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] The term *scripting language* is sometimes used in a wider sense, to refer to dynamic high-level programming languages in general.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Some are strictly interpreted languages, while others use a form of compilation.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] In this context, the term *script* refers to a small program in such a language.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Typically, a script is contained in a single file, and no larger than a few thousand lines of code.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] The scope of scripting languages ranges from small to large, and from highly domain-specific language to general-purpose programming languages.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] A language may start as small and highly domain-specific and later develop into a portable and general-purpose language; conversely, a general-purpose language may later develop special domain-specific dialects.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Script is a subjective characterization that generally includes the following attributes.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] A script is usually not compiled, at least not its usual meaning.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Generally, they are interpreted directly from source code, or from bytecode, or run as native after just-in-time compilation.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] A script is generally relatively short and simple.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] As there is no limit on size or complexity, script is subjective.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] A few lines of code without branching is probably considered a script.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] A codebase of multiple files, that performs sophisticated user or hardware interface or complicated algorithms or multiprogramming is probably not considered a script.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] A script usually automates a task that would otherwise be performed by a person in a more manual way.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] A language that is primarily intended for scripting generally has limited capabilities compared to a general-purpose language.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] A scripting language may lack the functionality to write complex applications.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Typically, a script starts executing at the first line of code whereas an application typically starts at a special point in the code called the entry point.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] For example, Java is not script-like since an application starts at the function named `main` which need not be at the top of the code.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] The following code starts at `main`, then calls `printHelloWorld` which prints "Hello World".
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] In contrast, the following Python code prints "Hello World" without the `main` function or other syntax such as a class definition required by Java.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Scripts are often created or modified by the person executing them, but they are also often distributed, such as when large portions of games are written in a scripting language, notably the Google Chrome T-rex game.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Early mainframe computers (in the 1950s) were non-interactive, instead using batch processing.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] IBM's Job Control Language (JCL) is the archetype of languages used to control batch processing.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] The first interactive shells were developed in the 1960s to enable remote operation of the first time-sharing systems, and these used shell scripts, which controlled running computer programs within a computer program, the shell.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Calvin Mooers in his TRAC language is generally credited with inventing *command substitution*, the ability to embed commands in scripts that, when interpreted, insert a character string into the script.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Louis Pouzin wrote an early processor for command scripts called RUNCOM for CTSS around 1964.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Stuart Madnick at MIT wrote a scripting language for IBM's CP/CMS in 1966.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] He originally called this processor COMMAND, later named EXEC.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Multics included an offshoot of CTSS RUNCOM, also called RUNCOM.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] EXEC was eventually replaced by EXEC 2 and Rexx.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Languages such as Tcl and Lua were specifically designed as general-purpose scripting languages that could be embedded in any application.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Other languages such as Visual Basic for Applications (VBA) provided strong integration with the automation facilities of an underlying system.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Embedding of such general-purpose scripting languages instead of developing a new language for each application also had obvious benefits, relieving the application developer of the need to code a language translator from scratch and allowing the user to apply skills learned elsewhere.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Some software incorporates several different scripting languages.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Modern web browsers typically provide a language for writing extensions to the browser itself, and several standard embedded languages for controlling the browser, including JavaScript (a dialect of ECMAScript) or XUL.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Scripting languages can be categorized into several different types, with a considerable degree of overlap among the types.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Scripting is often contrasted with system programming, as in Ousterhout's dichotomy or "programming in the large and programming in the small".
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] In this view, scripting is glue code, connecting software components, and a language specialized for this purpose is a *glue language*.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Pipelines and shell scripting are archetypal examples of glue languages, and Perl was initially developed to fill this same role.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Web development can be considered a use of glue languages, interfacing between a database and web server.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] But if a substantial amount of logic is written in script, it is better characterized as simply another software component, not "glue".
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Macro languages exposed to operating system or application components can serve as glue languages.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] These include Visual Basic for Applications, WordBasic, LotusScript, CorelScript, Hummingbird Basic, QuickScript, Rexx, SaxBasic, and WinWrap Basic.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Other tools like AWK can also be considered glue languages, as can any language implemented by a Windows Script Host engine (VBScript, JScript and VBA by default in Windows and third-party engines including implementations of Rexx, Perl, Tcl, Python, XSLT, Ruby, Modern Pascal, Delphi, and C).
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] A majority of applications can access and use operating system components via the object models or its own functions.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Depending upon the OS version, WSH and the default script engines (VBScript and JScript) are available.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Programmable calculators can be programmed in glue languages in three ways.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] For example, the Texas Instruments TI-92, by factory default can be programmed with a command script language.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Inclusion of the scripting and glue language Lua in the TI-NSpire series of calculators could be seen as a successor to this.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] The primary on-board high-level programming languages of most graphing calculators (most often Basic variants, sometimes Lisp derivatives, and more uncommonly, C derivatives) in many cases can glue together calculator functions—such as graphs, lists, matrices, etc.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Third-party implementations of more comprehensive Basic version that may be closer to variants listed as glue languages in this article are available—and attempts to implement Perl, Rexx, or various operating system shells on the TI and HP graphing calculators are also mentioned.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] A number of text editors support macros written either using a macro language built into the editor, e.g., The SemWare Editor (TSE), vi improved (VIM), or using an external implementation, e.g., XEDIT, or both, e.g., KEDIT.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Sometimes text editors and edit macros are used under the covers to provide other applications, e.g., FILELIST and RDRLIST in CMS .
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Many of these languages' interpreters double as command-line interpreters such as the Unix shell or the MS-DOS `COMMAND.COM`.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Others, such as AppleScript offer the use of English-like commands to build scripts.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] With the advent of graphical user interfaces, a specialized kind of scripting language emerged for controlling a computer.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] These languages interact with the same graphic windows, menus, buttons, and so on, that a human user would.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] They do this by simulating the actions of a user.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] These languages are typically used to automate user actions.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Such languages are also called *macros* when control is through simulated key presses or mouse clicks, and tapping or pressing on a touch-activated screen.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] These languages could in principle be used to control any GUI application, but in practice their use is limited because they need support from the application and from the operating system.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] There are a few exceptions to this limit.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Some GUI scripting languages are based on recognizing graphical objects from their display screen pixels.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] These GUI scripting languages do not depend on support from the operating system or application.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] When the GUI provides the appropriate interfaces, as in the IBM Workplace Shell, a generic scripting language, e.g., Object REXX, can be used to write GUI scripts.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Likewise, many computer game systems use a custom scripting language to express the programmed actions of non-player characters and the game environment.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Languages of this sort are designed for a single application; while they may superficially resemble a specific general-purpose language (e.g., QuakeC, modeled after C), they have custom features that distinguish them.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Emacs Lisp, while a fully formed and capable dialect of Lisp, contains many special features that make it most useful for extending the editing functions of Emacs.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] An application-specific scripting language can be viewed as a domain-specific programming language specialized to one application.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] A number of languages have been designed for the purpose of replacing application-specific scripting languages by being embeddable in application programs.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] The application programmer (working in C or another systems language) includes "hooks" where the scripting language can control the application.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] These languages may be technically equivalent to an application-specific extension language but when an application embeds a "common" language, the user gets the advantage of being able to transfer skills from application to application.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] A more generic alternative is simply to provide a library (often a C library) that a general-purpose language can use to control the application, without modifying the language for the specific domain.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] JavaScript began as, and still is mostly, a language for scripting inside web browsers.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] However, the standardizing of the language as ECMAScript has made it popular as a general-purpose embeddable language.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] The Mozilla implementation SpiderMonkey is embedded in several environments such as the Yahoo Widgets Engine,and applications such as the Adobe products Flash (ActionScript) and Acrobat (for scripting PDF files).
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Tcl was created as an extension language but has come to be used more often as a general-purpose language in roles similar to Python, Perl, and Ruby.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] In contrast, Rexx was created as a job control language, but is widely used as an extension language and a general-purpose language.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Perl is a general-purpose language, but had the Oraperl (1990) dialect, consisting of a Perl 4 binary with Oracle Call Interface compiled in.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] This has however since been replaced by a library (Perl Module), DBD::Oracle.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Other complex and task-oriented applications may incorporate and expose an embedded programming language to allow their users more control and give them more functionality than can be available through a user interface, no matter how sophisticated.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] For example, Autodesk Maya 3D authoring tools embed the Maya Embedded Language, or Blender which uses Python to fill this role.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] Some other types of applications that need faster feature addition or tweak-and-run cycles (e.g. game engines) also use an embedded language.
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] During the development, this allows them to prototype features faster and tweak more freely, without the need for the user to have intimate knowledge of the inner workings of the application or to rebuild it after each tweak (which can take a significant amount of time).
[src:tcl-lang/scripting-language] The scripting languages used for this purpose range from the more common and more famous Lua and Python to lesser-known ones such as AngelScript and Squirrel.
[src:tcl-lang/wiki-tcl-lang-org] Tcl is a simple-to-learn yet very powerful programming language.
[src:tcl-lang/wiki-tcl-lang-org] Its syntax is described in just a dozen rules, but it has all the features needed to rapidly create useful programs in almost any field of application - on a wide variety of international platforms.
[src:tcl-lang/wiki-tcl-lang-org] It allows you to develop graphical applications that run on Windows, Linux, MacOS X and many other platforms.
[src:tcl-lang/wiki-tcl-lang-org] And not just from Tcl - Tk can be used from many languages including C, Ruby, Perl, Python and Lua.
